You'll want to use a `sync.WaitGroup` to coordinate your goroutines! It allows you to wait until a collection of goroutines have finished. Here's how to integrate it:

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"sync"
	"time"
)

func fetchData(id int, wg *sync.WaitGroup) {
	defer wg.Done() // Decrements the counter when the goroutine finishes
	fmt.Printf("Goroutine %d: Starting data fetch...\n", id)
	time.Sleep(time.Duration(id) * time.Second) // Simulate work
	fmt.Printf("Goroutine %d: Finished data fetch.\n", id)
}

func main() {
	var wg sync.WaitGroup // Create a WaitGroup

	for i := 1; i <= 3; i++ {
		wg.Add(1) // Increment the counter for each goroutine
		go fetchData(i, &wg) // Pass the WaitGroup by pointer
	}

	wg.Wait() // Block until the counter is zero
	fmt.Println("All goroutines have finished. Main function exiting.")
}
```
This setup ensures `main` waits for all `fetchData` goroutines to complete their tasks before proceeding. Feel free to ask if you have more Go questions!

