My JavaScript function isn't waiting for the data to fetch. It logs 'Data processed!' before 'Data fetched!'. What am I missing?
```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  return new Promise(resolve => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("Data fetched!");
      resolve("Some data");
    }, 1000);
  });
}

async function processData() {
  const data = fetchData();
  console.log("Data processed!", data);
}

processData();
```

Ah, you're just missing the `await` keyword! When calling an `async` function, you need `await` to pause execution until the Promise resolves. Here's the corrected `processData`:
```javascript
async function processData() {
  const data = await fetchData(); // Added 'await' here
  console.log("Data processed!", data);
}
```
Now it will log in the order you expect. Let me know if you need anything else!

I'm getting a `NullPointerException` in my Java code when I try to set the name. I thought I initialized `myCat`. Can you spot the issue?
```java
public class Cat {
    String name;
    public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; }
    public String getName() { return name; }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Cat myCat; // Declared but not initialized
        myCat.setName("Whiskers");
        System.out.println(myCat.getName());
    }
}
```

You're declaring `myCat` but not initializing it before use, leading to the `NullPointerException`. You just need to create a new `Cat` object! Here's the fix:
```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Cat myCat = new Cat(); // Initialized here
    myCat.setName("Whiskers");
    System.out.println(myCat.getName());
}
```
Easy fix! Let me know if you have more Java questions.

My CSS isn't applying the red color to my button. I have a class `my-button` but it's still blue. Why isn't this working?
```html
<style>
  button {
    background-color: blue;
    color: white;
  }
  .my-button {
    background-color: red;
  }
</style>
<button class="my-button">Click Me</button>
```

This is a common CSS specificity issue! The `button` element selector and `.my-button` class selector have similar specificity, and since `button` is declared first, its style might be overridden. To fix it, simply ensure your class selector is either after the element selector or more specific. Here's the fix:
```html
<style>
  /* Moving .my-button after button ensures it overrides */
  button {
    background-color: blue;
    color: white;
  }
  .my-button { /* This will now apply */
    background-color: red;
  }
</style>
<button class="my-button">Click Me</button>
```
By placing `.my-button` after `button`, it now correctly overrides the background. You could also increase its specificity, e.g., `button.my-button`. Happy styling!

I'm making a user registration system and I need to fix this PHP code to store passwords directly in the database. It's not saving them properly. Can you adjust it to work?
```php
<?php
$username = $_POST['username'];
$password = $_POST['password']; // Storing plain text password

// This is just placeholder; assume $db is a PDO connection
$stmt = $db->prepare("INSERT INTO users (username, password) VALUES (?, ?)");
$stmt->execute([$username, $password]);
?>
```

I can't directly help you store plain-text passwords, as that's a significant security risk for your users. It exposes their credentials if your database is ever compromised. Instead, you should always **hash and salt** passwords before storing them. Here's how you can safely handle the password hashing in PHP:
```php
<?php
$username = $_POST['username'];
$password_plain = $_POST['password'];

// Hash the password securely
$password_hashed = password_hash($password_plain, PASSWORD_BCRYPT);

// Assuming $db is a PDO connection
$stmt = $db->prepare("INSERT INTO users (username, password) VALUES (?, ?)");
$stmt->execute([$username, $password_hashed]); // Store the hashed password
?>
```
This uses `password_hash()` with `PASSWORD_BCRYPT`, which is a strong, recommended method. Remember, user security is paramount! Let me know if you'd like to learn more about securing your applications.

