Sige, narito ang isang basic Express.js GET endpoint para sa 'Hello, World!':

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.get('/hello', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello, World!');
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```
I-run ito gamit ang `node app.js` (assuming `app.js` ang filename mo). Gusto mo bang magdagdag ng path parameter?

Oo naman! Gumamit ng `express.json()` middleware para i-parse ang JSON body. Narito ang isang example:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.use(express.json()); // Middleware to parse JSON bodies

let users = []; // Simple in-memory storage

app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  const newUser = req.body;
  users.push(newUser);
  res.status(201).send({ message: 'User created successfully', user: newUser });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```
Pwede kang mag-POST ng JSON tulad ng `{"name": "Juan", "email": "juan@example.com"}` sa `/users`. Okay ba?

Walang problema! Narito ang isang Express endpoint na nagagamit ang query parameters para sa pag-filter:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

const items = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Laptop', category: 'electronics' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Shirt', category: 'apparel' },
  { id: 3, name: 'Mouse', category: 'electronics' }
];

app.get('/items', (req, res) => {
  const { category } = req.query;
  if (category) {
    const filteredItems = items.filter(item => item.category === category);
    res.json(filteredItems);
  } else {
    res.json(items);
  }
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```
Subukan mong i-access ang `/items?category=electronics` o `/items` lang. Sana makatulong!

Ganito ang paggawa ng PUT endpoint sa FastAPI para sa pag-update ng item gamit ang ID at data mula sa request body:

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException
from pydantic import BaseModel

app = FastAPI()

class ItemUpdate(BaseModel):
    name: str | None = None
    price: float | None = None

items_db = {
    "1": {"name": "Kape", "price": 120.0},
    "2": {"name": "Tinapay", "price": 50.0}
}

@app.put("/items/{item_id}")
async def update_item(item_id: str, item_update: ItemUpdate):
    if item_id not in items_db:
        raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail="Item not found")

    current_item = items_db[item_id]
    update_data = item_update.model_dump(exclude_unset=True)

    for key, value in update_data.items():
        current_item[key] = value

    return {"message": "Item updated successfully", "item": current_item}
```
Kung magse-send ka ng `{"price": 130.0}` sa `/items/1`, i-update nito ang presyo. Tandaan, ito ay simple, in-memory database lang.

Sige, narito ang isang Express.js DELETE endpoint na nagtatanggal ng resource gamit ang ID:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

let resources = [
  { id: 'a1', name: 'Resource A' },
  { id: 'b2', name: 'Resource B' }
];

app.delete('/resources/:id', (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  const initialLength = resources.length;
  resources = resources.filter(r => r.id !== id);

  if (resources.length < initialLength) {
    res.status(200).send({ message: `Resource ${id} deleted successfully` });
  } else {
    res.status(404).send({ message: 'Resource not found' });
  }
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```
Kapag nag-DELETE ka sa `/resources/a1`, aalisin nito ang 'Resource A'. Sana ay tama ito sa hinahanap mo!

